description: Launched on 20th May 1989, It's Wicked! was Marvel UK's foray into producing a comic of supernaturally-themed humour strips, aimed at the market that was previously served by titles such as Monster Fun and Shiver and Shake. Unlike most non-reprint Marvel UK titles, it was neither set in the Marvel universe nor were most of the strips licensed properties. Strips included Gordon Gremlin, Inspector Spectre, Ghostman Bat and his Black and White Rat, Clare Voyant, Best of Fiends, Toad in the Hole, Dunstable D. Dragon, Winnie the Witch Doctor, Mummy's Boy, Ghoul School and Ghosthunters. The cover star was Slimer from Ghostbusters. Only 17 issues were produced before the title was cancelled.
name: It's Wicked!

description: Having previously had his U.S. adventures reprinted in a variety of Marvel U.K. titles, on 25th February 1981 Captain America received his own U.K. title. As with the majority of British comics of this era, the interiors were black and white, the title was an anthology, with Cap initially sharing his comic with Iron Man, Defenders and Dazzler, and the early issues included free gifts to entice buyers to try the comic out - in this case, the first two issues included stickers of Marvel characters. Starting with the 21st issue, the title absorbed Marvel Action, whose Fantastic Four strip replaced Defenders, and Marvel Super Adventure was similarly incorporated into Captain America with issue 37, bringing with it glossy covers, Daredevil and a handful of colour pages per issue. Captain America cancelled on April 3rd 1982 with its 59th issue.
name: Captain America

description:
Alan Class title launched in the 1960s, reprinting stories from various US comics from a number of different publishers. One of the company's shorter lived titles, it cancelled after 23 issues, but was later relaunched in the 1970s, restarting at #1. It lasted 10 issues. Also, the series numbers do not correspond back and forth. For example, issue #1 of this series matches #9 of the later series.

Note for anyone uploading new issues: Since Alan Class titles deliberately carried no date and the second volume restarted from #1, it is easy to mistake one volume for the other. The clue to getting it right is the price. Britain used shillings up until 1970, so the 1960s series' issues are priced with a shilling symbol (e.g. 1'-) while the 1970s series' issues are priced in pence (e.g. 5p)
name: Out of This World

description: In the 1950s British publisher L. Miller and Son held a license to reprint Fawcett's Captain Marvel and his related titles in the U.K., and were publishing Captain Marvel and Captain Marvel Jr. However, in 1953, after a punishing legal battle with DC Comics over claims that Captain Marvel infringed DC's Superman copyrights, Fawcett ceased publication and decided not to renew L. Miller's license. Since Captain Marvel and Captain Marvel Jr. were two of their more popular titles, Len Miller enlisted the assistance of artist and writer Mick Anglo to come up with a rescue plan. He created new characters, Marvelman, Young Marvelman and Kid Marvelman to replace Captain Marvel, Captain Marvel Jr. and Mary Marvel respectively, and, with #25, cover dated 3rd February 1954, L. Miller's two reprint titles were renamed Marvelman and Young Marvelman and began publishing stories produced by Mick Anglo's studio. Both were highly successful, and ran until #370 in February 1963, although towards the end, after Mick Anglo left the titles, they began reprinting old stories. There were also 8 Young Marvelman Annuals, plus one titled Marvelman Jr.
name: Young Marvelman

description:
After being hired by Thorpe & Porter, in 1965 Mick Anglo sought to produce a title in the vein of his previous biggest success, Marvelman. Having already produced Super Hombre for Editorial Ferma in 1958 to sell to the Spanish market, Anglo began reprinting those strips in English as Miracle Man. The title lasted 13 issues, a much shorter run than its Spanish counterpart's 68 issues.

NB: Despite stories to the contrary, the Miracle Man/Super Hombre strips were not simple retouched Marvelman strips. Though the characters had similar powers, the stories were not duplicates of Anglo's previously published UK work.
name: Miracle Man

description:
In 1958 Editorial Ferma asked Mick Anglo to produce a comic for the Spanish market. He created Super Hombre, a character with similar powers but a distinctly different origin to his existing creation, Marvelman. The series lasted 68 issues. In 1965, when Top Sellers asked Anglo to produce a superhero title for them, he reprinted some of Super Hombre's stories in English, changing the character name to Miracle Man.

NB: Despite claims to the contrary, Super Hombre's stories are apparently not simply redrawn Marvelman strips, but were instead scripted by Spanish writer Juan Llarch and drawn by Spanish artist Giralt (Emilio Giralt Ferrando).
name: Super Hombre
